### Describe the bug

`InterceptorManager` stores interceptors in a plain array (`this.handlers`). When `eject(id)` is called, it sets the slot to `null` rather than removing it:

In applications that frequently add and remove interceptors (e.g., per-request auth interceptors, retry logic), this causes unbounded growth of the `handlers` array with `null` entries. Every request dispatch must filter these out.

### Steps to reproduce

const instance = axios.create();

for (let i = 0; i < 10_000; i++) {
  const id = instance.interceptors.request.use((cfg) => cfg);
  instance.interceptors.request.eject(id);
}

// handlers array now has 10,000 null slots
console.log(instance.interceptors.request.handlers.length); // 10000

### Expected behavior

The `handlers` array should not grow unboundedly. Ejected interceptors should not leave behind `null` tombstones that accumulate over the lifetime of an axios instance.

### Suggested fix

Replace the Array with a Map keyed by an incrementing integer ID:

constructor() {
  this.handlers = new Map();
  this._idCounter = 0;
}

use(fulfilled, rejected, options) {
  const id = this._idCounter++;
  this.handlers.set(id, {
    fulfilled,
    rejected,
    synchronous: options?.synchronous ?? false,
    runWhen: options?.runWhen ?? null,
  });
  return id;
}

eject(id) {
  this.handlers.delete(id);
}

This is a non-breaking change — the returned ID is still a number and eject(id) still works the same way from the caller's perspective.

### Environment

- axios version: v1.x (latest)
- Affected file: lib/core/InterceptorManager.js

## Bug Description

`AxiosHeaders.get(name, true)` internally calls `parseTokens` to split a structured header value into its token/parameter pairs. When a parameter value is a **quoted-string** (wrapped in `""`) as permitted by RFC 9110 §5.6.4, the double-quote delimiters are incorrectly included in the returned value.

## Reproduction

```js
import axios from 'axios';

// Simulate a response with a quoted boundary parameter (common in multipart responses)
const headers = new axios.AxiosHeaders();
headers.set('content-type', 'multipart/form-data; boundary="----=_Part_123"');

const tokens = headers.get('content-type', true);
console.log(tokens.boundary);
// Actual:   '----=_Part_123'   ← includes the surrounding DQUOTE characters
// Expected: '----=_Part_123'     ← DQUOTE delimiters must be stripped per RFC 9110
```

## Related second issue

The regex `[^,;]+` used in `parseTokens` also captures trailing whitespace before a delimiter. So `charset=utf-8   ;` yields `'utf-8   '` instead of `'utf-8'`.

## Root Cause

In `lib/core/AxiosHeaders.js`, the `parseTokens` function assigns `match[2]` (the raw captured token value) directly to `tokens[match[1]]` without:
1. Stripping surrounding double-quotes (required by RFC 9110 §5.6.4)
2. Trimming trailing whitespace

## Impact

Any code that uses `headers.get('content-type', true)` and checks `tokens.boundary` will receive the value with quotes, causing string comparison failures. This affects multipart form data processing where the `Content-Type` boundary is frequently quoted by browsers and servers.

## Expected Behavior

Per [RFC 9110 §5.6.4](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9110#section-5.6.4):
> A quoted-string is a sequence of zero or more characters enclosed within double-quotes. The initial and final DQUOTE characters are not part of the value.

use case: custom `AxiosRequestConfig` field

```ts
import axios from 'axios';

export const someFlag = Symbol('some flag used in request interceptor')

declare module 'axios' {
  export interface AxiosRequestConfig {
    [someFlag]?: boolean
  }
}

await axios.get('/api/dashboard', { [someFlag]: true });
```

but current `mergeConfig` is using [`Object.keys`](https://github.com/axios/axios/blob/v1.17.0/lib/core/mergeConfig.js#L114) which is `owned enumerable string keys`, symbol keys are not included in `Object.keys`, cause the configured value always `undefined` in interceptors

When using this package in a Next.js application, it seems like the bundler is adding the `buffer` node module so it is available in the browser.

This package only uses the Buffer when [converting to form data](https://github.com/axios/axios/blob/a8e4f13aeecc45a3b8fab3ecfd9ddb5d70fb772b/lib/helpers/toFormData.js#L141). We can look into alternatives that don't include the buffer module, like Uint8Array or similar browser-native APIs.

---

To reproduce the issue:

Create a Next.js application from a template

```bash
# Create app
yarn create next-app analyze-bundles-app

# Navigate to the directory
cd analyze-bundles-app

# Install the module
yarn axios
```


Update `app/page.tsx` to use the module

```tsx
"use client";
import axios from "axios";
import { useEffect } from "react";

export default function Home() {
  useEffect(() => {
    axios
      .get("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1")
      .then((response) => {
        console.log(response.data);
      });
  }, []);
  return <div>hello world</div>;
}

```

Make a production build with the analyzer plugin

```bash
yarn next experimental-analyze
```

When the reports are created, open http://localhost:4000 and see that the buffer module is included in the bundle.

